		<li id="comment-34" class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1">
			<article id="div-comment-34" class="comment-body">
				<footer class="comment-meta">
					<div class="comment-author vcard">
						<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/8ad5d3d8091918ad5b107d2557c8bbb5?s=34&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F0.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D34&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-34 photo' height='34' width='34' />						<b class="fn"><a href='http://gravatar.com/rbotguy' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Robotguy</a></b> <span class="says">says:</span>					</div><!-- .comment-author -->

					<div class="comment-metadata">
						<a href="http://everett.x10.mx/2012/01/21/vetinaris-clock-a-clock-that-ticks-irregularly/#comment-34">
							<time datetime="2012-10-08T11:26:48+00:00">
								October 8, 2012 at 11:26 am							</time>
						</a>
											</div><!-- .comment-metadata -->

									</footer><!-- .comment-meta -->

				<div class="comment-content">
					<p>I&#8217;m looking into building one also (the Ikea clock in my cubicle currently has two wires dangling from it that are soldered to the coil, just waiting for the next step). </p>
<p>My plan is to power with 2xAA and connect one side of the coil to the point between the batteries. The other side of the coil will connect to an I/O pin.  If I leave the I/O pin hi-Z most of the time taking the pin HI will give a +1.5V pulse, and LO will give a -1.5V pulse. Since the number HI/LO pulses are always equal, the batteries should discharge evenly.</p>
				</div><!-- .comment-content -->

				<div class="reply">
					<a class='comment-reply-link' href='/2012/01/21/vetinaris-clock-a-clock-that-ticks-irregularly/?replytocom=34#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("div-comment-34", "34", "respond", "165")'>Reply</a>				</div><!-- .reply -->
			</article><!-- .comment-body -->
</li><!-- #comment-## -->
	</ol><!-- .comment-list -->

	
	
	
